                      shows the storage moduli of PMMA and various composites. The storage modulus of PMMA is increased by the stiffening effect of the nanotubes, which is particularly significant at higher temperatures. For example, the modulus is increased by a factor of 1.6–2.0 at 40°C whereas it shows a 5–27-fold increase at 120°C. In addition, the presence of carbon nanotubes also enables the matrix to sustain a high modulus value to higher temperature. The ratio of the modulus at 120°C to that at 40°C is only 0.03 for PMMA, but 0.50 for the composite containing 26 wt.% nanotube ([FIG4]
                     ).
